## Conclusion and Opinion

The Holocaust was the result of a complex convergence of historical prejudices, political upheaval, economic crises, ideological fanaticism, and war. While Adolf Hitler and the Nazi leadership were central architects, the genocide was enabled by widespread societal antisemitism, institutional complicity, and international inaction.

It is critical to recognize that the Holocaust was not an inevitable event but one that grew gradually from deep-rooted hatred and was facilitated by human choices at many levels. Understanding these causes in detail is essential to preventing future genocides.

The evidence shows that the Holocaust started because of entrenched antisemitism exploited by a totalitarian regime that used propaganda, pseudo-science, legal persecution, and war to systematically dehumanize and annihilate the Jewish people. The complicity of ordinary people and the failure of the international community to intervene early also played significant roles.

